{"key":"processedPost-16611010","value":{"id":16611010,"first":16610718,"last":16616762,"when":1343591633,"utime":"07/29/12 10:53 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Doc_T said:</strong><br />It's not impossible.<br />RR has talked about rehydrating small slivers of dry flesh and then starting them on agar.<br />And there's probably some spores in there, dried up in a cap.<br />With some agar dishes and patience it's a project that's within reach.</blockquote><br />Reviving dry tissue has been a mushroom propagation technique for at least 150 years.&nbsp; Mycelium can and does dry completely out, and then after being rehydrated start growing again.&nbsp; Mushroom hunters in the PNW sees this every year when the downed trees hosting oyster mushrooms dry totally out to crispy dry all summer, and then freeze solid in below zero temps all winter.&nbsp; Then, following the snow melt the following spring, they fruit prolifically.<br />I've revived long dry mushroom tissue several times.&nbsp; It's been photodocumented here.&nbsp; You can find it with a search.<br />RR","title":"Re: possible cultivation from dried shrooms"}}